# Codacy MCP Rules

Configuration for AI behavior when interacting with Codacy's MCP Server.

> **Important**: This workspace uses Codacy exclusively through the MCP API tools (`codacy_list_tools`, `codacy_get_pattern`). Local CLI analysis (`codacy_cli_analyze`) is NOT used because it requires Docker/WSL on Windows. For local linting use ESLint directly; for security scanning use Trivy directly.

## Available MCP tools and when to use them

| Tool                 | Works on Windows | Purpose                                                  |
| -------------------- | ---------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| `codacy_list_tools`  | Yes              | Discover available analysis tools and their capabilities |
| `codacy_get_pattern` | Yes              | Get full details of a specific lint/security pattern     |
| `codacy_cli_analyze` | No (needs WSL)   | Local analysis -- **do NOT call this tool**              |
| `codacy_cli_install` | No (needs WSL)   | CLI installer -- **do NOT call this tool**               |

## When to use Codacy MCP

### Pattern lookup

- When the user asks about a specific linting rule or security pattern, use `codacy_get_pattern` with the pattern ID and tool UUID
- Present the pattern explanation so the user understands why an issue matters
- Use the pattern details to propose targeted fixes

### Tool discovery

- When the user asks what analysis tools Codacy supports, run `codacy_list_tools`
- Use results to recommend the right tool for their stack (eslint for JS/TS, pylint for Python, pmd for Java, etc.)

### Code review context

- During PR reviews, if a pattern name or rule ID is mentioned, look it up with `codacy_get_pattern` for full context
- Cross-reference Codacy patterns with project ESLint config to check for gaps

## What NOT to do

- **Do NOT call `codacy_cli_analyze`** -- it will fail with "CLI on Windows is not supported without WSL"
- **Do NOT call `codacy_cli_install`** -- same limitation
- **Do NOT suggest installing Codacy CLI** via brew, npm, npx, or any package manager
- **Do NOT block workflow** waiting for Codacy analysis that will never complete

## Local analysis alternatives

Instead of Codacy CLI, use these tools directly (already configured in pre-commit hooks):

| Need                       | Tool          | How                                                   |
| -------------------------- | ------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| JS/TS linting              | ESLint        | `pnpm lint` or via lint-staged                        |
| Code formatting            | Prettier      | `pnpm format:check` or via lint-staged                |
| Type checking              | TypeScript    | `tsc --noEmit`                                        |
| Secret scanning            | Trivy         | `trivy fs --scanners secret .`                        |
| Dependency vulnerabilities | Trivy         | `trivy fs --scanners vuln --severity HIGH,CRITICAL .` |
| Code health                | CodeScene MCP | `code_health_score` / `code_health_review`            |

## Severity-based response policy

When reviewing code or patterns from Codacy:

- **Critical / High** (security vulnerabilities, SQL injection, XSS): Flag immediately, block merge if in PR review
- **Medium** (code smells, potential bugs, deprecated API usage): Note and suggest fix
- **Low / Info** (style, minor naming): Mention only if relevant to current work

## When Codacy MCP tools are unavailable

- Reset the MCP server in Cursor settings (Settings > MCP)
- Verify the Codacy MCP server is enabled and running
- Restart Cursor if the server appears stuck
- If none work, continue without Codacy -- fall back to ESLint + Trivy for local analysis

## Whenever a Codacy tool returns a 404 error

- The repository may not be configured in Codacy
- Suggest adding the repository through the Codacy web dashboard (codacy.com)
- This is optional -- local tools (ESLint, Trivy, CodeScene) cover the core needs

## Coordination with other tools

| Tool                  | Responsibility                                       | Where it runs                 |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| **Codacy MCP**        | Pattern/rule queries, tool discovery                 | Cursor agent (API calls)      |
| **Codacy Web**        | Historical dashboard, PR analysis, trends            | codacy.com (optional)         |
| **CodeScene MCP**     | Code health, complexity, auto-refactoring, tech debt | Cursor agent (local)          |
| **ESLint + Prettier** | Linting + formatting                                 | Pre-commit hook (lint-staged) |
| **Trivy**             | Secrets + dependency vulnerabilities                 | Pre-commit hook + manual      |
| **TypeScript**        | Type checking                                        | Pre-commit hook               |
